Evaluating Opportunistic Routing Protocols 
content:
1 ABSTRACT :
1-1:Traditional mobile ad hoc network routing protocols assume that contemporaneous end to end communication paths exist between data senders and receivers .
1-2:In some mobile ad hoc networks with a sparse node population, an end to end communication path may break frequently or may not exist at any time .
1-3:Many routing protocols have been proposed in the literature to address the problem, but few were evaluated in a realistic opportunistic network setting .
1-4:We use simulation and contact traces (derived from logs in a production network) to evaluate and compare five existing protocols: direct delivery, epidemic, random, PRoPHET, and Link State, as well as our own proposed routing protocol .
1-5:We show that the direct delivery and epidemic routing protocols suffer either low delivery ratio or high resource usage, and other protocols make tradeoffs between delivery ratio and resource usage .
1-6:C.2.4 [Computer Systems Organization]: Computer .
2 INTRODUCTION :
2-1:Mobile opportunistic networks are one kind of delay tolerant network [6] .
2-2:Delay tolerant networks provide service despite long link delays or frequent link breaks .
2-3:Long link delays happen in networks with communication between nodes at a great distance, such as interplanetary networks [2] .
2-4:Link breaks are caused by nodes moving out of range, environmental changes, interference from other moving objects, radio power offs, or failed nodes .
2-5:For us, mobile opportunistic networks are those DTNs with sparse node population and frequent link breaks caused by power offs and the mobility of the nodes .
2-6:Mobile opportunistic networks have received increasing interest from researchers .
2-7:In the literature, these networks include mobile sensor networks [25], wild animal tracking networks [11], pocketswitched networks [8], and transportation networks [1, 14] .
2-8:We expect to see more opportunistic networks when the one laptopper child project [18] starts rolling out inexpensive laptops with wireless networking capability for children in developing countries, where often no infrastructure exits .
2-9:Opportunistic networking is one promising approach for those children to exchange information .
2-10:One fundamental problem in opportunistic networks is how to route messages from their source to their destination .
2-11:Mobile opportunistic networks differ from the Internet in that disconnections are the norm instead of the exception .
2-12:In mobile opportunistic networks, communication devices can be carried by people [4], vehicles [1] or animals [11] .
2-13:Some devices can form a small mobile ad hoc network when the nodes move close to each other .
2-14:But a node may frequently be isolated from other nodes .
2-15:Note that traditional Internet routing protocols and ad hoc routing protocols, such as AODV [20] or DSDV [19], assume that a contemporaneous endto end path exists, and thus fail in mobile opportunistic networks .
2-16:Indeed, there may never exist an end to end path between two given devices .
2-17:In this paper, we study protocols for routing messages between wireless networking devices carried by people .
2-18:We assume that people send messages to other people occasionally, using their devices; when no direct link exists between the source and the destination of the message, other nodes may relay the message to the destination .
2-19:Each device represents a unique person (it is out of the scope of this paper when a device maybe carried by multiple people) .
2-20:Each message is destined for a specific person and thus for a specific node carried by that person .
2-21:Although one person may carry multiple devices, we assume that the sender knows which device is the best to receive the message .
2-22:We do not consider multicast or geocast in this paper .
2-23:Many routing protocols have been proposed in the literature .
2-24:Few of them were evaluated in realistic network settings, or even in realistic simulations, due to the lack of any realistic people mobility model .
2-25:Random walk or random way point mobility models are often used to evaluate the performance of those routing protocols .
2-26:Although these synthetic mobility models have received extensive interest by mobile ad hoc network researchers [3], they do not reflect people"s mobility patterns [9] .
2-27:Realising the limitations of using random mobility models in simulations, a few researchers have studied routing protocols in mobile opportunistic networks with realistic mobility traces .
2-28:Chaintreau et al .
2-29:[5] theoretically analyzed the impact of routing algorithms over a model derived from a realistic mobility data set .
2-30:Su et al .
2-31:[22] simulated a set of routing 35 protocols in a small experimental network .
2-32:Those studies help researchers better understand the theoretical limits of opportunistic networks, and the routing protocol performance in a small network (20 30 nodes) .
2-33:Deploying and experimenting large scale mobile opportunistic networks is difficult, we too resort to simulation .
2-34:Instead of using a complex mobility model to mimic people"s mobility patterns, we used mobility traces collected in a production wireless network at Dartmouth College to drive our simulation .
2-35:Our messagegeneration model, however, was synthetic .
2-36:To the best of our knowledge, we are the first to simulate the effect of routing protocols in a large scale mobile opportunistic network, using realistic contact traces derived from real traces of a production network with more than 5, 000 users .
2-37:Using realistic contact traces, we evaluate the performance of three naive routing protocols (direct delivery, epidemic, and random) and two prediction based routing protocols, PRoPHET [16] and Link State [22] .
2-38:We also propose a new prediction based routing protocol, and compare it to the above in our evaluation. .
3 ROUTING PROTOCOL :
3-1:A routing protocol is designed for forwarding messages from one node (source) to another node (destination) .
3-2:Any node may generate messages for any other node, and may carry messages destined for other nodes .
3-3:In this paper, we consider only messages that are unicast (single destination) .
3-4:DTN routing protocols could be described in part by their transfer probability and replication probability; that is, when one node meets another node, what is the probability that a message should be transfered and if so, whether the sender should retain its copy .
3-5:Two extremes are the direct delivery protocol and the epidemic protocol .
3-6:The former transfers with probability 1 when the node meets the destination, 0 for others, and no replication .
3-7:The latter uses transfer probability 1 for all nodes and unlimited replication .
3-8:Both these protocols have their advantages and disadvantages .
3-9:All other protocols are between the two extremes .
3-10:First, we define the notion of contact between two nodes .
3-11:Then we describe five existing protocols before presenting our own proposal .
3-12:A contact is defined as a period of time during which two nodes have the opportunity to communicate .
3-13:Although we are aware that wireless technologies differ, we assume that a node can reliably detect the beginning and end time of a contact with nearby nodes .
3-14:A node may be in contact with several other nodes at the same time .
3-15:The contact history of a node is a sequence of contacts with other nodes .
3-16:Node i has a contact history Hi(j), for each other node j, which denotes the historical contacts between node i and node j .
3-17:We record the start and end time for each contact; however, the last contacts in the node"s contact history may not have ended .
3-18:2.1 Direct Delivery Protocol In this simple protocol, a message is transmitted only when the source node can directly communicate with the destination node of the message .
3-19:In mobile opportunistic networks, however, the probability for the sender to meet the destination may be low, or even zero .
3-20:2.2 Epidemic Routing Protocol The epidemic routing protocol [23] floods messages into the network .
3-21:The source node sends a copy of the message to every node that it meets .
3-22:The nodes that receive a copy of the message also send a copy of the message to every node that they meet .
3-23:Eventually, a copy of the message arrives at the destination of the message .
3-24:This protocol is simple, but may use significant resources; excessive communication may drain each node"s battery quickly .
3-25:Moreover, since each node keeps a copy of each message, storage is not used efficiently, and the capacity of the network is limited .
3-26:At a minimum, each node must expire messages after some amount of time or stop forwarding them after a certain number of hops .
3-27:After a message expires, the message will not be transmitted and will be deleted from the storage of any node that holds the message .
3-28:An optimization to reduce the communication cost is to transfer index messages before transferring any data message .
3-29:The index messages contain IDs of messages that a node currently holds .
3-30:Thus, by examining the index messages, a node only transfers messages that are not yet contained on the other nodes .
3-31:2.3 Random Routing An obvious approach between the above two extremes is to select a transfer probability between 0 and 1 to forward messages at each contact .
3-32:We use a simple replication strategy that allows only the source node to make replicas, and limits the replication to a specific number of copies .
3-33:The message has some chance of being transferred to a highly mobile node, and thus may have a better chance to reach its destination before the message expires .
3-34:2.4 PRoPHET Protocol PRoPHET [16] is a Probabilistic Routing Protocol using History of past Encounters and Transitivity to estimate each node"s delivery probability for each other node .
3-35:When node i meets node j, the delivery probability of node i for j is updated by pij = (1 − pij)p0 + pij, (1) where p0 is an initial probability, a design parameter for a given network .
3-36:Lindgren et al .
3-37:[16] chose 0.75, as did we in our evaluation .
3-38:When node i does not meet j for some time, the delivery probability decreases by pij = αk pij, (2) where α is the aging factor (α < 1), and k is the number of time units since the last update .
3-39:The PRoPHET protocol exchanges index messages as well as delivery probabilities .
3-40:When node i receives node j"s delivery probabilities, node i may compute the transitive delivery probability through j to z with piz = piz + (1 − piz)pijpjzβ, (3) where β is a design parameter for the impact of transitivity; we used β = 0.25 as did Lindgren [16] .
3-41:2.5 Link State Protocol Su et al .
3-42:[22] use a link state approach to estimate the weight of each path from the source of a message to the destination .
3-43:They use the median inter contact duration or exponentially aged intercontact duration as the weight on links .
3-44:The exponentially aged inter contact duration of node i and j is computed by wij = αwij + (1 − α)I, (4) where I is the new inter contact duration and α is the aging factor .
3-45:Nodes share their link state weights when they can communicate with each other, and messages are forwarded to the node that have the path with the lowest link state weight .
