4 TIMELY CONTACT PROBABILITY :
4-1:We also use historical contact information to estimate the probability of meeting other nodes in the future .
4-2:But our method differs in that we estimate the contact probability within a period of time .
4-3:For example, what is the contact probability in the next hour? Neither PRoPHET nor Link State considers time in this way .
4-4:One way to estimate the timely contact probability is to use the ratio of the total contact duration to the total time .
4-5:However, this approach does not capture the frequency of contacts .
4-6:For example, one node may have a long contact with another node, followed by a long non contact period .
4-7:A third node may have a short contact with the first node, followed by a short non contact period .
4-8:Using the above estimation approach, both examples would have similar contact probability .
4-9:In the second example, however, the two nodes have more frequent contacts .
4-10:We design a method to capture the contact frequency of mobile nodes .
4-11:For this purpose, we assume that even short contacts are sufficient to exchange messages.1 The probability for node i to meet node j is computed by the following procedure .
4-12:We divide the contact history Hi(j) into a sequence of n periods of ΔT starting from the start time (t0) of the first contact in history Hi(j) to the current time .
4-13:We number each of the n periods from 0 to n − 1, then check each period .
4-14:If node i had any contact with node j during a given period m, which is [t0 + mΔT, t0 + (m + 1)ΔT), we set the contact status Im to be 1; otherwise, the contact status Im is 0 .
4-15:The probability p (0) ij that node i meets node j in the next ΔT can be estimated as the average of the contact status in prior intervals: p (0) ij = 1 n n−1X m=0 Im .
4-16:(5) To adapt to the change of contact patterns, and reduce the storage space for contact histories, a node may discard old history contacts; in this situation, the estimate would be based on only the retained history .
4-17:The above probability is the direct contact probability of two nodes .
4-18:We are also interested in the probability that we may be able to pass a message through a sequence of k nodes .
4-19:We define the k order probability inductively, p (k) ij = p (0) ij + X α p (0) iα p (k−1) αj , (6) where α is any node other than i or j .
4-20:3.1 Our Routing Protocol We first consider the case of a two hop path, that is, with only one relay node .
4-21:We consider two approaches: either the receiving neighbor decides whether to act as a relay, or the source decides which neighbors to use as relay .
4-22:3.1.1 Receiver Decision Whenever a node meets other nodes, they exchange all their messages (or as above, index messages) .
4-23:If the destination of a message is the receiver itself, the message is delivered .
4-24:Otherwise, if the probability of delivering the message to its destination through this receiver node within ΔT is greater than or equal to a certain threshold, the message is stored in the receiver"s storage to forward 1 In our simulation, however, we accurately model the communication costs and some short contacts will not succeed in transfer of all messages .
4-25:to the destination .
4-26:If the probability is less than the threshold, the receiver discards the message .
4-27:Notice that our protocol replicates the message whenever a good looking relay comes along .
4-28:3.1.2 Sender Decision To make decisions, a sender must have the information about its neighbors" contact probability with a message"s destination .
4-29:Therefore, meta data exchange is necessary .
4-30:When two nodes meet, they exchange a meta message, containing an unordered list of node IDs for which the sender of the metamessage has a contact probability greater than the threshold .
4-31:After receiving a meta message, a node checks whether it has any message that destined to its neighbor, or to a node in the node list of the neighbor"s meta message .
4-32:If it has, it sends a copy of the message .
4-33:When a node receives a message, if the destination of the message is the receiver itself, the message is delivered .
4-34:Otherwise, the message is stored in the receiver"s storage for forwarding to the destination .
4-35:3.1.3 Multi node Relay When we use more than two hops to relay a message, each node needs to know the contact probabilities along all possible paths to the message destination .
4-36:Every node keeps a contact probability matrix, in which each cell pij is a contact probability between to nodes i and j .
4-37:Each node i computes its own contact probabilities (row i) with other nodes using Equation (5) whenever the node ends a contact with other nodes .
4-38:Each row of the contact probability matrix has a version number; the version number for row i is only increased when node i updates the matrix entries in row i .
4-39:Other matrix entries are updated through exchange with other nodes when they meet .
4-40:When two nodes i and j meet, they first exchange their contact probability matrices .
4-41:Node i compares its own contact matrix with node j"s matrix .
4-42:If node j"s matrix has a row l with a higher version number, then node i replaces its own row l with node j"s row l .
4-43:Likewise node j updates its matrix .
4-44:After the exchange, the two nodes will have identical contact probability matrices .
4-45:Next, if a node has a message to forward, the node estimates its neighboring node"s order k contact probability to contact the destination of the message using Equation (6) .
4-46:If p (k) ij is above a threshold, or if j is the destination of the message, node i will send a copy of the message to node j .
4-47:All the above effort serves to determine the transfer probability when two nodes meet .
4-48:The replication decision is orthogonal to the transfer decision .
4-49:In our implementation, we always replicate .
4-50:Although PRoPHET [16] and Link State [22] do no replication, as described, we added replication to those protocols for better comparison to our protocol. .
5 EVALUATION RESULTS :
5-1:We evaluate and compare the results of direct delivery, epidemic, random, PRoPHET, Link State, and timely contact routing protocols .
5-2:4.1 Mobility traces We use real mobility data collected at Dartmouth College .
5-3:Dartmouth College has collected association and disassociation messages from devices on its wireless network wireless users since spring 2001 [13] .
5-4:Each message records the wireless card MAC address, the time of association disassociation, and the name of the access point .
5-5:We treat each unique MAC address as a node .
5-6:For 37 more information about Dartmouth"s network and the data collection, see previous studies [7, 12] .
5-7:Our data are not contacts in a mobile ad hoc network .
5-8:We can approximate contact traces by assuming that two users can communicate with each other whenever they are associated with the same access point .
5-9:Chaintreau et al .
5-10:[5] used Dartmouth data traces and made the same assumption to theoretically analyze the impact of human mobility on opportunistic forwarding algorithms .
5-11:This assumption may not be accurate,2 but it is a good first approximation .
5-12:In our simulation, we imagine the same clients and same mobility in a network with no access points .
5-13:Since our campus has full WiFi coverage, we assume that the location of access points had little impact on users" mobility .
5-14:We simulated one full month of trace data (November 2003) taken from CRAWDAD [13], with 5, 142 users .
5-15:Although predictionbased protocols require prior contact history to estimate each node"s delivery probability, our preliminary results show that the performance improvement of warming up over one month of trace was marginal .
5-16:Therefore, for simplicity, we show the results of all protocols without warming up .
5-17:4.2 Simulator We developed a custom simulator.3 Since we used contact traces derived from real mobility data, we did not need a mobility model and omitted physical and link layer details for node discovery .
5-18:We were aware that the time for neighbor discovery in different wireless technologies vary from less than one seconds to several seconds .
5-19:Furthermore, connection establishment also takes time, such as DHCP .
5-20:In our simulation, we assumed the nodes could discover and connect each other instantly when they were associated with a same AP .
5-21:To accurately model communication costs, however, we simulated some MAC layer behaviors, such as collision .
5-22:The default settings of the network of our simulator are listed in Table 1, using the values recommended by other papers [22, 16] .
5-23:The message probability was the probability of generating messages, as described in Section 4.3 .
5-24:The default transmission bandwidth was 11 Mb s .
5-25:When one node tried to transmit a message, it first checked whether any nearby node was transmitting .
5-26:If it was, the node backed off a random number of slots .
5-27:Each slot was 1 millisecond, and the maximum number of backoff slots was 30 .
5-28:The size of messages was uniformly distributed between 80 bytes and 1024 bytes .
5-29:The hop count limit was the maximum number of hops before a message should stop forwarding .
5-30:The time to live was the maximum duration that a message may exist before expiring .
5-31:The storage capacity was the maximum space that a node can use for storing messages .
5-32:For our routing method, we used a default prediction window ΔT of 10 hours and a probability threshold of 0.01 .
5-33:The replication factor r was not limited by default, so the source of a message transferred the messages to any other node that had a contact probability with the message destination higher than the probability threshold .
