5-37:When there were more contacts during a certain period, there was a higher likelihood that a new message was generated in that period .
5-38:This correlation is not unreasonable, since there were more movements during the day than during the night, and so the number of contacts .
5-39:Figure 1 shows the statistics of the numbers of movements and the numbers of contacts during each hour of the day, summed across all users and all days .
5-40:The plot shows a clear diurnal activity pattern .
5-41:The activities reached lowest around 5am and peaked between 4pm and 5pm .
5-42:We assume that in some applications, network traffic exhibits similar patterns, that is, people send more messages during the day, too .
5-43:Messages expire after a TTL .
5-44:We did not use proactive methods to notify nodes the delivery of messages, so that the messages can be removed from storage .
5-45:4.4 Metrics We define a set of metrics that we use in evaluating routing protocols in opportunistic networks: • delivery ratio, the ratio of the number of messages delivered to the number of total messages generated .
5-46:• message transmissions, the total number of messages transmitted during the simulation across all nodes .
5-47:38 • meta data transmissions, the total number of meta data units transmitted during the simulation across all nodes .
5-48:• message duplications, the number of times a message copy occurred, due to replication .
5-49:• delay, the duration between a message"s generation time and the message"s delivery time .
5-50:• storage usage, the max and mean of maximum storage (bytes) used across all nodes .
